ets swapped, but the swap partner is NOT consumed by any gate at all (because it was another gate's output that feeds into different downstream gates)?\n\nIn a valid adder circuit, every wire is either a final output (z) or consumed by exactly the right downstream gates. If a carry is swapped with a wire from a different part of the circuit, the swap will always be detectable because:\n1. The carry won't be found as input to the expected downstream gates\n2. The swap partner won't be in the expected position either\n\nMy bit-by-bit trace handles this by:\n- When `findGate('XOR', t, carry)` fails (carry is wrong), it looks for the non-initial XOR that uses carry, or the one that uses t\n- When it finds the correct gate, it identifies the swap partner\n\nI think the algorithm is robust. Let me add one more stress test with a larger adder and make sure it handles a wider variety of swap patterns."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3409,"cache_read_input_tokens":90543,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":3409},"output_tokens":4,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9f8f558c-94d3-44f4-b683-194683c83de6","uuid":"71157fec-2830-4ccd-9d7e-0bb9137584b6"}
